<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n36189e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36189e">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36189e"> 189(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ever to be blamed / Mannahatten / 3 jolly topers ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Another etymology &hellip; is found in certain letters still extant, which passed between the early governors and their neighboring powers, wherein it is called indifferently Monhattoes, Munhatos, and Manhattoes, which are evidently unimportant variations of the same name; &hellip; the opinion of the worthy Dominie Heckwelder &hellip; ascribes the name to a great drunken bout held on the island by the Dutch discoverers, whereat they made certain of the natives most ecstatically drunk for the first time in their lives; who, being delighted with their jovial entertainment, gave the place the name of <mark>Mannahattanink, that is to say, The Island of Jolly Topers</mark>: a name which it continues to merit in the present &hellip; Having thus provided the embryo city <font color="green">[Manno-hata]</font> with <font color="green">[an honest Christian]</font> name <font color="green">[New Amsterdam]</font>, the next was to give it an armorial bearing a device &hellip; so, after mature deliberation, a sleek beaver was emblazoned on the city standard, as indicative of the amphibious origin and patient, persevering habits of the New Amsterdammers. <small> Washington Irving, <a name="WINY" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WINY"><cite title="source">A History of New York, by Diedrich Knickerbocker</cite></a> (ed. unknown) 60ff</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c09107e" href="c09all.htm#c09107e">VI.C.09:107(e)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
